    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "Article",
    "headline": "Best Wok Cooking Guide",
    "description": "Master wok cooking with our comprehensive guide covering wok selection, seasoning, essential tools, wok hei, heat management, 15 essential stir-fry recipes, and a complete sauce guide.",
    "url": "https://28grams.vip/wok-cooking-guide",
    "author": {
      "@type": "Organization",
      "name": "28grams"
    }
  },
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": [
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What is the best material for a wok?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Carbon steel is generally considered the best material for a wok. It heats up quickly, responds rapidly to temperature changes, and develops a natural non-stick patina over time. Cast iron is heavier and retains heat longer, while stainless steel is durable but prone to sticking."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How do I season a new carbon steel wok?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "First, scrub off the factory oil with soap and hot water. Dry thoroughly, then heat the wok until the metal changes color (usually to a blueish tint). Swirl a high-smoke-point oil around the surface, wipe away the excess with a paper towel, and heat until it stops smoking. Repeat this process a few times."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What are the essential tools for wok cooking?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "The key tools are a wok spatula (chuan) for tossing, a spider or skimmer for removing fried foods, and a wok ring if you are using a round-bottom wok on a standard Western stove."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What is 'Wok Hei'?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Wok hei, or 'breath of the wok,' refers to the complex, smoky flavor created when oil droplets catch fire momentarily as food is tossed over extreme heat. It requires high heat and constant movement."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How should I manage heat when using a wok?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Stir-frying relies on high heat. Pre-heat your wok until smoking before adding oil. Cook in small batches so the wok's temperature doesn't drop significantly. If the heat is too low, the food will steam or boil instead of searing."
        }
      }
    ]
  }
];

