<div class="content">
  <h2>Choosing a Wok</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Carbon Steel:</strong> The standard choice for wok cooking. It's lightweight, heats up rapidly, and develops a natural non-stick surface (patina) with proper seasoning. Best overall for home cooks and professionals alike.</li>
    <li><strong>Cast Iron:</strong> Heavier and takes longer to heat up, but retains heat exceptionally well. A good option if you have a weaker burner, as it won't drop in temperature as quickly when food is added. Requires seasoning.</li>
    <li><strong>Stainless Steel:</strong> Durable and doesn't require seasoning, but it's prone to sticking. It's also heavy and doesn't respond as quickly to temperature changes. Not recommended for typical stir-frying.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>The Seasoning Process</h2>
  <p>Seasoning a carbon steel or cast iron wok protects it from rust and creates a non-stick surface.</p>
  <ol>
    <li>Wash the wok thoroughly with soap and water to remove the factory protective coating. Dry completely.</li>
    <li>Place the wok over high heat until the metal changes color (often blue or grey).</li>
    <li>Swirl a small amount of high-smoke-point oil (like peanut or vegetable oil) around the surface.</li>
    <li>Wipe the excess oil with a paper towel and heat until it stops smoking. Let it cool, and repeat 2-3 times.</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>Essential Wok Tools</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Wok Spatula (Chuan):</strong> A long-handled spatula shaped to contour the wok's curved sides. Essential for tossing and scooping.</li>
    <li><strong>Spider or Skimmer:</strong> A wire mesh basket on a long handle. Perfect for safely retrieving deep-fried or blanched foods from hot oil or water.</li>
    <li><strong>Wok Ring:</strong> If you use a traditional round-bottomed wok on a standard Western flat-top or grate stove, a ring provides stability.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Wok Hei & Heat Management</h2>
  <p><strong>Wok Hei</strong> ("breath of the wok") is the distinct, complex, smoky flavor achieved when tiny droplets of oil aerosolize and catch fire briefly as food is tossed over intense heat. It requires a powerful burner and constant agitation.</p>
  <p><strong>Heat Management</strong> is crucial. Always pre-heat your wok before adding oil. Cook in small batches; overloading the wok drops the temperature too much, causing food to steam or boil in its own juices instead of searing. Keep ingredients moving constantly to prevent burning while maintaining high heat.</p>

  <h2>Sauce Guide</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Soy Sauce:</strong> The backbone of many Asian cuisines. <em>Light soy sauce</em> is saltier and thinner, used for general seasoning. <em>Dark soy sauce</em> is thicker, sweeter, and primarily used for adding a rich color to dishes.</li>
    <li><strong>Oyster Sauce:</strong> A thick, savory, sweet, and slightly briny sauce made from oyster extract. Great for thickening stir-fry sauces and adding umami.</li>
    <li><strong>Hoisin Sauce:</strong> A thick, sweet, and tangy sauce often used as a glaze for meats (like Char Siu) or as a dipping sauce. Made from fermented soybeans, garlic, and chilies.</li>
    <li><strong>Fish Sauce:</strong> Pungent and salty, made from fermented fish. Essential in Southeast Asian cooking (like Thai and Vietnamese) for adding deep umami flavor. Use sparingly.</li>
  </ul>

